{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "College leaders say that by focusing on what people know, not how or when they learn it, and by tapping new technology, they can save students time and lower costs.", "abstract": "Seat-time system of college credit, in which college degrees are earned based on time spent in class, is being challenged by programs based on tangible evidence of learning; some innovators say that focusing on what people learn, not how or when they learn it, and utilizing new technologies can save students time and lower costs.", "section_name": "Education", "print_page": "26", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Anya", "role": "reported", "lastname": "KAMENETZ", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}], "original": "By ANYA KAMENETZ", "contributor": ""}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/03/education/edlife/degrees-based-on-what-you-can-do-not-how-long-you-went.html", "lead_paragraph": "College leaders say that by focusing on what people know, not how or when they learn it, and by tapping new technology, they can save students time and lower costs.", "headline": {"seo": "Degrees Based on What You Can Do, Not How Long You Went", "main": "Are You Competent? Prove It.", "print_headline": "Are You Competent? Prove It."}, "_id": "526fa35a38f0d81489d1692e", "word_count": "2066", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2013/11/03/education/edl-03competency-t_CA0/edl-03competency-t_CA0-thumbWide-v2.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2013/11/03/education/edl-03competency-t_CA0/edl-03competency-t_CA0-thumbWide-v2.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 575, "url": "images/2013/11/03/education/edl-03competency-t_CA0/edl-03competency-t_CA0-articleLarge-v2.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2013/11/03/education/edl-03competency-t_CA0/edl-03competency-t_CA0-articleLarge-v2.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "575"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "